<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%>
	   <a name=104865156629412></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f104865156629412><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=104865156629412>Levels 55-56 solo in "Neriak 2" =)</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=104865156629412#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=184766><span id=Sage>jmspiers</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>16 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Mar 25th 11:41 PM 2003</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Hey Folks!<br><br>NOTE: This is kind of a long post, but hey it's detailed at least =).<br><br>On a lot of different mage boards I have seen people searching for a good place for soloing level 55 and 56. Most mages know that the experience is incredible in Neriak 3rd Gate and HHK until you ding 55 and the mobs turn light blue. Unfortunately a lot of mages, including myself until recently, are still in search of that &quot;Neriak 2&quot;.<br><br>After reading a lot of different posts and seeing mages talk about being stuck making 1/2 blue and 1 blue an hour regular exp at level 55 and 56, I decided to share the place that I found. It's a spot that some of you may have been to before, I know that I had, but I discovered a spot in a spot (if that doesn't make sense now it will later) that is extremely good exp. So if you've been to the place that I'm about to talk about, please read through the whole strategy and try it out before you turn me off, I promise that it will be worth your while =).<br><br>Before I give a give the strategy here is a little bit of information about the results to expect. First, if you haven't done so already, I'd recommend downloading the player window UI mod from <a href="http://www.graffe.com." target=_new>http://www.graffe.com.</a> It turns your player window into a window that shows your level exp bar, AA exp bar, mana, hp, health, pet health, ac, and attack, along with the exact percentages for each one. So at a glance you can see exactly what pct exp or AA exp you are getting in 10 minutes, 20 minutes, or per kill, or however you want to track it. <br><br>Installing a UI mod is very simple. There are plenty of detailed instructions on the net, but basically just open your EQ folder (in my case C:/program files/sony/everquest trilogy) and open the &quot;ui files&quot; folder. Make a new subfolder (in my case I named it &quot;playerwindow&quot;), and copy the .xml file that you downloaded into the folder. Load up the game and type &quot;load playerwindow 1&quot;. It will take a few seconds, your screen will refresh and it will be loaded. <br><br>Ok enough about that! Now about the results.<br><br>I did exactly 49 pct of level 55 here in one evening. It was a longer game night than normal, but 1/2 of level 55 in one night isn't shabby. At level 56 I get exactly 25pct AA an hour, or between 6-8pct regular exp (about 2 blue). Again not shabby. The only place that I have personally found that can rival this kind of exp at this level is a fast pulling group in PoN. At level 56 every 10 minutes I get 4-5pct AA. In addition to this I make 150-300 plat an hour, plus some nice item drops that will sell for several hundred plat in the bazaar. Still not good enough for you? Well if you're into the faction thing then loot the canines from the mobs that I'm about to talk about and give them to the Sergeant at the human settlement for Qeynos Guard faction (and a couple of other factions).<br><br>Interested? Read on.<br><br>The place? Gnoll caves in Jagged Pine.<br><br>Been there before camping the entrance of pit and am not sure why I'm so pumped about the exp? Well, here's the strategy.<br><br>I was in the gnoll caves at 55, bored out of my mind, stuck in a hell level, and on my way to the pit trap (called &quot;dead end hall&quot; by some) to camp gnolls like I had always done before. It was already camped, very fortunately for me, because I never would have found my new spot otherwise. At the time another 55 mage friend was there in JP soloing as well, so he jumped down in the pit with me and we started moving farther back just clearing stuff as we went. I had never gone to the very back of the gnoll caves before because of all the roamers that add in the tunnels (in a moment I'll talk about a way to avoid that). I had either camped the entrance rooms or the pit trap.<br><br>Well, as we move back through the tunnels not really paying attention to where we were going, we get to the very back. There is a HUGE room back there. I had seen it on maps but never gone back because I assumed that there would be a lot of gnolls. There are a lot of gnolls, but they are stagnant spawns, very far apart! There are NO roamers! I took a 52 druid guildy back there and there was room enough for him to quad around the other spawns, that's how big the room is!<br><br>At the bottom of this post I have linked to a map showing the best route to get back there, invis'd, bypassing almost all mobs that see invis. But first a bit more on the strategy.<br><br>All of the gnolls in the giant cavern can be single fought, except for a couple in the very back. Me and some friends solo up here in this cavern all the time now, and I can say from personal experience that it can support 2 56 mages and a 56 shammy and never run out of spawns. If you do happen to get the cavern empty just pull from the tunnels, there are plenty more there. We have never seen anyone else but us back there. The spawn time on all mobs is 13 minutes +/- 1 or 2.<br><br>Almost all of these mobs are melee (darkpaw gnoll warriors). They have roughly 4-6k hp I would guess and max hit for 111 damage (a joke to the 51 earth pet). There are a few casters too that spawn back there. Here is the strategy for taking these down (note that you can do this earlier than 55, even as early as 52, but I would really recommend Neriak 3rd Gate or HHK until 55).<br><br>When killing the warriors the strategy is simple. Cast the 51 earth pet, BO 3 or 4 it, give it ds, and send it in. It will run neck and neck with the warriors. Do NOT cast on the mob or heal the pet, it's just a waste of mana. When the warrior is at 1/2 bubble health, &quot;eat&quot; your pet (using Broom of Trilon or other items). The warrior will still be rooted, but even if root breaks it will just try to run very very slowly. Cast scars of sigil and finish it off. Using this strategy you will NEVER run out of mana w/ KEI and a horse. I'm assuming with no horse there might be a tad of downtime, but not much since with the earth pet rooting the mobs you can just sit through the fight.<br><br>(On a side note, the reason I recommend the earth pet over air is because if the mobs run far there is a danger of adds).<br><br>Come across a caster? No problem. There are several kinds of casters that spawn back there. The Defilers and Corruptors are necromancers. The Curates and Oracles are clerics and will CH themselves. The strategy for killing any of these is the same. Send pet in and immediately Sirocco the mob. If all 3 land then it's dead before it can heal itself, but if one wave is resisted simply cast scars of sigil and kill it. I love the casters because they literally die in under 10 seconds, and give just as good exp as the warriors.<br><br>That's it as far as the strategy goes. There is one thing that I ask. If you try this before level 55, or if you try this using an old school style strategy (i.e. send pet in...heal pet....nuke...heal pet...nuke...heal pet...nuke) and you burn all your mana on one fight and get bad exp please don't flame me for it =). If you haven't practiced chain casting pets before then at least give it a shot, it's the best way to get exp at 55+ imho.<br><br>Here is a link to a map of Jagged Pine from eqatlas.com. <br><br><a href="http://www.geocities.com/reeshan2002/jproute.html" target=_new>http://www.geocities.com/reeshan2002/jproute.html</a><br><br>I have marked the best route into the cavern with a blue line. There are some casters along the route that see invis but they can be bypassed by hugging the walls. If they are in the hall then just wait a moment and they will move. You can also just fight your way in if you like, although you can get up to 6 adds from roamers in the halls so I'd recommend just invis'ng to the back.<br><br>Anyway I hope that this helps you all as much as it has helped me. I am convinced that this is possibly the best solo exp possible OVER TIME for levels 55-56. What I mean by this is that you can always solo in PoJ and PoD and get better exp per kill, but in timed runs I found that JP gnoll caves is much better per hour because you avoid all the downtime and time spent hunting for single pulls in the planes.<br><br>Good luck all!<br>&nbsp;<br>Baron Reeshan Ragefire, Magus of the 56th Flame, Drinal<br>Mathurin Kerbouchard, Bard of the 36th Song, Drinal<br>Lenrok Thunderwolf, Warrior of the 37th Circle, Drinal</td></tr>
